'''Mazeltov''' is a [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] word meaning "good luck" but is often used in place of "congratulations."  Like other [[blessings]] it is often said frequently and sometimes loudly at [[Jewish]] [[weddings]] as well as [[Bar Mitzvah]]s.  It is commonly used within the Jewish community.  In colloquial languange, "Mazel tov" is sometimes said sarcastically when congratulations are not appropriate or due.

According to the [[American Heritage Dictionary]] the word comes ultimately from the [[Akkadian language]] ''manzaltu, mazzaztum,'' "position of a star," from ''izuzzu,'' "to stand") + ṭôb, "good." This became the [[Mishnaic Hebrew]] expression ''mazzāl ṭôb,'' based on  mazzāl, meaning "[[constellation]]" or "[[destiny]]." [http://www.answers.com/mazel+tov&r=67]

